00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:03.520
<v Speaker 1>There should be something to it.

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:04.720
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:09.280
<v Speaker 1>Another commonplace that we use the mood tense in Spanish.

00:01:09.439 --> 00:01:17.840
<v Speaker 1>is when we say it is an adjective, ke, and then a verb, this verb is going to go into the mood tense.

00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:26.740
<v Speaker 1>You are noticing that ke has a lot to do with the subjunctive, that this ke introduces the mood tense in many cases.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:37.380
<v Speaker 1>So, for example, if I want to give you some advice and tell you it's terrible that you eat this, it is terrible that you eat this.

00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:39.620
<v Speaker 1>So let's speak informally

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:46.300
<v Speaker 2>Es terrible que comas esto.

00:01:46.300 --> 00:01:47.020
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:47.020 --> 00:01:50.300
<v Speaker 1>Es terrible que comas esto.

00:01:50.300 --> 00:01:51.260
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:59.180
<v Speaker 1>So it's the que, the combination of esterrible and ke which introduces this mood tense.

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:04.380
<v Speaker 1>If you say it is terrible if you eat this, then you don't use the mood tense

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:05.380
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say that?

00:02:05.380 --> 00:02:11.060
<v Speaker 1>It is terrible if you eat this, still speaking informally.

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:15.380
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:15.380 --> 00:02:18.500
<v Speaker 1>Es terrible si comes esto.

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:20.740
<v Speaker 1>How would you say it is possible?

